Module Ansible to upgrade VMtools:   "vmware_guest_tools_upgrade":
>If we want to write an ansible playbook to upgrade VMware tools we can:
        1.first check vmware tools status (task 1)
        2.check vmwaretools version
        3.copy the binary file from source to dest & use unarchive module (used to uncompressed the files from an archive file like zip
          ,tar,tar.gz
        4.the remote_src=yes : montre que le fichier archive n'est pas dans le node node controller Ansible 

      ex playbook (but not completed):
            
     - name: Copy VMtools Binaries From source to Destination server
       copy: src={{ src_bin_location }} dest={{dst_bin_location }}
    
     - name: Unarchive
       unarchive: src={{dst_bin_location}}VMwareTools-10.0.6-3560309.tar.gz dest={{dst_bin_location}} remote_src=yes
   
   
 >When we do an upgrade to VMware tools we do it by pointing on UUID of the VM OR MoId of the VM 
          -MoRef ID is a vmware internal identifier that is generated by vsphere when new objects
           are created in vCenter. ex: vm-512  (512 is just a counter)
          -UUID: ex: 501d6aa3-54fc-8b8d-99a2-e448463ead18 which represents a 128bit identifier

___________________________________________________________________________________________________

le module vmware_guest: 
_______________________

sert à créer des VMs from template (cloner vers un modèle) { si on a crée une vm from template ne va 
pas marcher au début car il faut lui donner un fichier iso ainsi que modifier la conf +il faut obligatory
de changer UUID car la création from template fait une copie de tout, et si on laisse la conf par défaut
il se peut que les vms produisent un conflit entre elles.

>Type d'allocation (disque):
   -Thin : consomme uniquement l'espace dont il a besoin
   -Thick: If you create a 50 GB virtual disk, that disk would consume
           exactly 50 GB of physical disk space

